Reconnecting with the very american Ideal of Labor Rights as Human Rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed legislation, which treats union organizing as a civil right and to protect.
"As unions go, so go middle-class jobs," says Ellison, the Democrat from Minnesota and a Progressive Caucus co-chair in Congress.
So I’m proud to introduce, with civil rights icon John Lewis, the Employee Empowerment Act.
This ground-breaking legislation will give workers the same legal options in case of discrimination for union organizing as for other forms of discrimination - stopping anti-union forces.
Amend of the National Labor Relations Act, by which opportunities for workers who suffer discrimination to organize trade union representatives, to sue for justice in civil court can be provided - and compensatory and punitive damages can be collected - is a meaningful and necessary initiative.
But it is with certainty not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
Indeed, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the cosponsors of their legislation are proposing, is a reconnection with a very American idea.
Despite the reverse, that unions have in recent years taken - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - Americans have once encouraged countries around the world that labor rights should be recognized, extended and respected.
There was a time, that millions of Americans still remember, when in this country democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right were mentioned in the same breath.
When the United States after World War II got Japan occupied, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his aides encouraged the country to make a constitution, which should assure that militarized autocracy of Hideki Tojo would be replaced with democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions had, in shaping the new Japan, a role to play, they used a language that explicitly recognized that "the right of workers to organize and to bargain and act collectively is guaranteed."
When the United States after World War II got Germany occupied, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides urged the Germans to write a constitution, that would assure that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced with muscular democracy.
Recognizing the truth, that workers would need to organize and make their voices in the new nation heard, the Germans included a provision that explicitly declared: "The right to form associations for working and economic conditions securing and improving shall be, to every individual and to every occupation or profession, guaranteed.
Agreements that restrict or seek to impair this right shall be null and void; measures directed to this end shall be unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, by which the Universal Declaration of Human Rights was drafted, as it was in 1948 by the United Nations adopted as a global covenant, Roosevelt and the other drafters included a guarantee that "everyone has the right, with which trade unions for the protection of his interests can be formed and joined."
For generations, Americans accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
As this country counseled other countries on how civil and democratic societies could be forged, Americans explained that the right to organize a trade union - and for this trade union, then in collective bargaining as an equal partner with corporations and government agencies, to get engaged - had to be protected.
With those rights in America under assault, it is indeed wise to get the American ideal reminded, that working people must have a right to unite and in a free and open society to make their voices heard.
As the Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. fifty years ago said :
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the labor movement did not the strength of the nation diminish but enlarged it.
By raising the living standards of millions, labor had miraculously a market for industry created and the whole nation to undreamed of production-levels lifted.
Those who have labor attacked forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers, as should we.
The formal recognition of labor rights as human rights - and the extension of protections of civil rights as protection to prevent discrimination against labor organizing - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are renewing ideals that in America have historically made it great and delivered the real promise of democracy .
Judge blocks temporarily law that could make all abortion clinics in Louisiana closed.
A U.S. federal judge blocked on Sunday temporarily enforcement of a law Louisiana that advocates say would likely have all five abortion clinics in the state closed.
The measure, signed by Bobby Jindal, Governor of Louisiana, in June into law and due to take effect Sept. 1, would require doctors who perform abortions to have patient admitting privileges at a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
The judge's ruling means, however, that doctors for the time being can continue to perform legal abortions while seeking such privileges.
"Plaintiffs will be allowed to lawfully operate, while for their efforts to obtain privileges, continuing," wrote federal Judge John deGravelles in the decision.
Within a month there will be a hearing scheduled for the judge to make a more permanent ruling on the law .  
Abortion rights activists applauded the decision , the latest in a string of rulings against similar measures , saying doctors have more time by which hospital privileges can be obtained.   
"Today's ruling ensures women in Louisiana are safe from an underhanded law that seeks, them of their health and rights, to strip," said Nancy Northup, president and chief executive of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which sued, on behalf of three of the state's five clinics, to block the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the ruling, to doctors from the two clinics, applied who were in the suit not plaintiffs and have also applied for admitting privileges.
Louisiana is among 11 states that have similar laws passed, with courts recently ruling such measures in Alabama and Mississippi as unconstitution.
Key parts of a law in Texas that would have shuttered most, in that state, remaining clinics were by a federal judge on Friday blocked.
Abortion rights campaigners, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admitting privileges laws impose medically unnecessary requirements on doctors.
Abortion opponents have countered that the measures aim to protect health of women, though some have also their effect of shuttering clinics lauded.
Only one doctor who in Louisiana performs abortions has hospital admitting privileges, said the Center for Reproductive Rights.
If all other doctors in the state are forced to stop more abortions-performing, that doctor, fearful for his safety, would stop carrying out the procedure, said the group.
In arguing against the ruling, said Louisiana officials, that they would not get doctors who perform abortions punished, while their applications for admitting privileges were pending.
