First spring day with wet and stormy weather conditions affects flights from Airport Adelaide
SPRING has given South Australia a wintry surprise, with heavy showers and strong winds affecting flights out of Airport Adelaide.
This evening by 9 pm, another 5mm of rain fell on the city, following 6.6mm that had already at sunday night fallen.
The latest precipitation was the result of a series of brief, blustery showers, including a downpour that began just before 8 p.m. and nearly 4mm of precipitation in about 10 minutes was provided.
After winter of last week provided an early dose of spring, temperatures in the city on Monday dropped again to a high of just 15.8 degrees.
Gusty weather conditions likely led to the delayed landing of a flight of Virgin Airlines from Melbourne to Adelaide.
The aircraft should have landed shortly after 7:30 pm, but got a wind shear hit - a sudden change in wind speed or direction over a short distance - and must take off through.
Wind gusts reached at this time about 50 km/h on the ground at Adelaide Airport.
Flight data showed that the aircraft also had to go through a second landing approach and finally touched down at about 8:40 pm.
The flight delay delayed subsequently several other flights, including an Emirates flight from Dubai and a Quantas flight from Sydney.
For Adelaide on Tuesday, a high temperature of 16°C is forecast, with possible showers.
